title: Texas Public Records Act Request: Flock Safety search audits, network sharing, and general order (Johnson County Sheriff)

communications.subject: Texas Public Information Act Request: Texas Public Records Act Request: Flock Safety search audits, network sharing, and general order (Johnson County Sheriff)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Texas Public Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Records related to the department’s Flock Safety system:
1. Organization Audit in Flock. 
The report should include data logged from the period of December 1, 2024, to the date this request is processed. Per Flock's documentation, the Organization Audit is available within the Insights tab and is defined as searches done within the agency.

2. Network Audit in Flock.
The report should include data logged from the period of December 1, 2024, to the date this request is processed. Per Flock's documentation, the Network Audit is available within the Insights tab and is defined as searches of the organization’s Flock network by any agency in the Flock System.

3. A list of network share settings that include:
3a. Flock networks shared with me
3b. Networks that I’m sharing

Please provide records in their original electronic, machine readable format. For example, please provide csv or spreadsheet files where applicable. Please do not redirect me to your transparency portal.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Paul Tepper

title: Arkansas Division of Correction Open Record Request - Quattrone Center

communications.subject: Arkansas Freedom of Information Act Request: Arkansas Division of Correction Open Record Request - Quattrone Center
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Arkansas Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Arkansas Division of Correction,

Dear Arkansas Division of Correction,

Pursuant to Arkansas freedom of Information Act Request (Ark. Code Ann. § 25-19-101, et seq.) I am requesting access to all records related to the purchase of field drug testing supplies and technologies (used to identify unknown substances that are potentially contraband) by your agency from January 1, 2016 to the present. 

1.	Specifically, I am requesting contracts your agency or department has with providers of drug testing kit or device providers (such as colorimetric or presumptive field tests or testing insurance), or any other records indicating the quantity, cost, vendor, and model of each item or system purchased. This request includes materials related to but not limited to the following:
o	Colorimetric or presumptive field test kits, such as: 
	NIK Public Safety kits 
	Sirchie NARK II kits
	Field Forensics DABIT kits
	Mistral drug identification/detection kits
	M.M.C. International B.V. presumptive drug tests
	TN Scientific Mandelin Reagent drug testing kits
	Macherey-Nagel MEDI-TEST
	Any other colorimetric or presumptive kits
o	Instrument-based technologies, including: 
	Raman spectroscopy devices
	Infrared (IR) spectroscopy devices
	Ion mobility spectrometry (IMS) devices
	Mass spectrometry (MS) devices
	Any other field-portable drug identification technologies
1.	Total annual budget allocated to the purchase or acquisition of such drug testing kits or devices.
2.	Spending information (such as invoices, purchase orders, or receipts) for any presumptive drug testing kits or devices.
3.	This request does not include urine, blood, or other tests designed to identify drug compounds in the human body. This request is made as part of an academic research project examining the use and cost of field drug testing technologies by law enforcement and correctional agencies nationwide. If possible, I request that the records be provided in electronic format (PDF, Excel, or CSV).

If any part of this request is denied, please provide a written explanation for the denial, including the specific exemption(s) relied upon. If the requested records are available in part, I request access to all segregable portions. Should there be any material cost (defined as more than $100) associated with providing the requested information, please provide me with an estimate before proceeding with any work.

Please contact me at QuattroneResearch@law.upenn.edu or 215-746-1251 if you have any questions or require clarification. Thank you for your time and assistance.

Sincerely,

 
Ross Miller
Assistant Director
Quattrone Center for the Fair Administration of Justice

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 3 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Sonny Albarado, a citizen of Arkansas, in coordination with Ross Miller.

Thanks for the update. Can you provide any additional info regarding the source of delays on this request, or the estimated delivery date? Please feel free to give me a call at 781-962-8816 if it'd be helpful to discuss the scope of the materials we're requesting.

communications.subject: RE: New Mexico Inspection of Public Records Act Request: Water Asset Management funds correspondence
communications.communication:
Dear Ms. Rock,

I am responding to your email yesterday requesting any additional info regarding the source of delays on this request. Please be assured that we make every effort to respond promptly to every request. However, we must also ensure that we are diligent and accurate in our reply. Thus, when obtained, all documents and emails must be reviewed. Additionally, we must rely on the state agency that controls the entire state email system to identify and provide the emails requested. As you can imagine, the process takes time.

As to an estimated response date, in our letter of August 1, 2023, we noted that we intend to respond by September 6, 2023.

Thank you for your patience and please feel free to contact me if you have further questions.

Respectfully,

[cid:image001.png@01D9C623.0D3F7D80]

communications.subject: ATTORNEY CLIENT PRIVILEGED - RE: [EXTERNAL] RE: New Mexico Inspection of Public Records Act Request: Water Asset Management funds correspondence
communications.communication:
Dear Ms. Rock and Ms. Burns,

Thank you for your inquiry and please accept our apologies for the delay.

As Mr. Scroggins noted in his August 3, 2023 email regarding our projected response, we always try to be prompt.  But as you might guess, the request references a large number of records.  As he said, we must thoroughly review all records to identify and obtain the responsive documents from both external and internal sources.  It is a complex and time-consuming process.

I am confident that we will have documents ready to provide on or before the December 6th, 2023, date noted in our recent communication.

Thank you for your continued patience!
Regards,
Renee



[cid:image002.png@01DA121F.C2136CB0]

Julia Rock

communications.subject: Re: Request for Inspection of Records
communications.communication:
Dear Ms. Rock and Ms. Burns:

As discussed in our letter of December 6, 2023, we are providing the records we currently have available in response to your June 16, 2023, request.  They are located at the website below:

MuckRock - Julia Rock<https://nmgov-my.sharepoint.com/:f:/r/personal/renee_garcia_erb_nm_gov/Documents/MuckRock%20-%20Julia%20Rock?csf=1&web=1&e=4gwfSH>

As also discussed, we will require additional time to provide the remainder of the records.  We plan to provide additional documents on or before February 1, 2024.  Thank you again for your continued patience regarding this matter.
Regards,
Renee



[cid:image001.png@01DA29F0.5D899B00]

title: Singh Mortality Review

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Singh Mortality Review
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

A copy of the IHSC Mortality Review for Jaspar Singh, who died in ICE Custody April 15, 2024, according to the Detainee Death Report ICE published: https://www.ice.gov/doclib/foia/reports/ddrSinghJaspar.pdf

I make this request as a member of the media, and therefore seek a fee waiver. Representative edited works based on prior FOIA requests like this one may be reviewed here: https://theappeal.org/authors/andrew-free/; and here: https://atlpresscollective.com/2025/01/31/new-record-sheds-light-on-unreported-death-in-atlanta-airport-customs-inspection/. 

I request expedited processing of this request pursuant to 6 CFR 5.5(e) and attest under penalty of perjury pursuant to 28 USC 1746 that the following statements are true and correct to the best of my knowledge and understanding: 
1. ICE deaths in custody in FY25 are currently on track to equal or surpass the 12 deaths in the previous fiscal year. 

2. IHSC Mortality Reviews provide an authoritative agency accounting of the medical circumstances of in-custody deaths. These reviews often conflict with the public-facing story the agency tells, raising critical questions about accountability, transparency, waste, fraud, and abuse. See https://phr.org/our-work/resources/deadly-failures-preventable-deaths-in-u-s-immigration-detention/.

3. The current administration's expansion of federal immigration detention is the subject of widespread and exceptional media interest in which there exist possible questions about the government's integrity which affect public confidence. See, e.g., 
a. https://www.newyorker.com/news/the-lede/how-many-immigrants-will-die-in-us-custody

communications.subject: ICE FOIA 2025-ICFO-25068
communications.communication:
03/13/2025 

Andrew  Free 
MuckRock News, DEPT MR182995 
Boston, Massachusetts 02115 

RE:	ICE FOIA Case Number 2025-ICFO-25068 
 
Dear Requester: 

This acknowledges receipt of your Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) request to U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement (ICE), dated 3/13/2025, your request for a waiver of all assessable FOIA fees, and your request for expedited treatment. Your request was received in this office on 3/13/2025. Specifically, you have requested records pertaining to a copy of the IHSC Mortality Review for Jaspar Singh, who died in ICE Custody April 15, 2024, according to the Detainee Death Report ICE published: https://www.ice.gov/doclib/foia/reports/ddrSinghJaspar.pdf. 

Due to the increasing number of FOIA requests received by this office, we may encounter some delay in processing your request. Per Section 5.5(a) of the DHS FOIA regulations, 6 C.F.R. Part 5, ICE processes FOIA requests according to their order of receipt. Although ICE’s goal is to respond within 20 business days of receipt of your request, the FOIA does permit a 10-day extension of this time period. As your request seeks numerous documents that will necessitate a thorough and wide-ranging search, ICE will invoke a 10-day extension for your request, as allowed by Title 5 U.S.C. § 552(a)(6)(B). If you’re able to narrow the scope of your request please contact our office. Narrowing the scope may speed up the search process. We will make every effort to comply with your request in a timely manner. 

Your request for expedited treatment is hereby denied. 

Under the DHS FOIA regulations, expedited processing of a FOIA request is warranted if the request involves “circumstances in which the lack of expedited treatment could reasonably be expected to pose an imminent threat to the life or physical safety of an individual,” 6 C.F.R. § 5.5(e)(1)(i), or “an urgency to inform the public about an actual or alleged federal government activity, if made by a person primarily engaged in disseminating information,” 6 C.F.R. § 5.5(e)(l)(ii).  Requesters seeking expedited processing must submit a statement explaining in detail the basis for the request, and that statement must be certified by the requester to be true and correct.  6 C.F.R. § 5.5(e)(3). 

Your request for expedited processing is denied because you do not qualify for either category under 6 C.F.R. § 5.5(e)(1).  You failed to demonstrate a particular urgency to inform the public about the government activity involved in the request beyond the public’s right to know about government activity generally.  Your letter was conclusory in nature and did not present any facts to justify a grant of expedited processing under the applicable standards. 

After thoroughly reviewing your letter and request for fee waiver, I have determined that you have not presented a convincing argument that you and/or your organization is entitled to a blanket waiver of applicable fees. 

The DHS FOIA Regulations at 6 CFR § 5.11(k)(2) set forth six factors to examine in determining whether the applicable legal standard for a fee waiver has been met.  We will consider these factors in our evaluation of your request for a fee waiver: 

(1) Whether the subject of the requested records concerns “the operations or activities of the government”; 
(2) Whether the disclosure is “likely to contribute” to an understanding of government operations or activities; 
(3) Whether disclosure of the requested information will contribute to the understanding of the public at large, as opposed to the individual understanding of the requestor or a narrow segment of interested persons; 
(4) Whether the contribution to public understanding of government operations or activities will be "significant"; 
(5) Whether the requester has a commercial interest that would be furthered by the requested disclosure; and 
(6) Whether the magnitude of any identified commercial interest to the requestor is sufficiently large in comparison with the public interest in disclosure, that disclosure is primarily in the commercial interest of the requestor. 

As a requester, you bear the burden under FOIA of showing that the fee waiver requirements have been met.  Based on my review of your 3/13/2025 letter and for the reasons stated herein, I have determined that your fee waiver request is deficient because your request did not satisfy factors 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, and 6. Since your request for a fee waiver has failed to satisfy each of the required factors, I am denying your fee waiver request. 

Provisions of the FOIA allow us to recover part of the cost of complying with your request.  We shall charge you for records in accordance with the DHS Interim FOIA regulations, as they apply to media requesters.  As a media requester, you will be charged 10 cents per page for duplication; the first 100 pages are free.  We will construe the submission of your request as an agreement to pay up to $25.00. You will be contacted before any further fees are accrued. 

If you deem the decision to deny expedited treatment and fee waiver for your request an adverse determination, you have the right to appeal.  Should you wish to do so, you must send your appeal and a copy of this letter, within 90 days of the date of this letter following the procedures outlined in the DHS FOIA regulations at 6 C.F.R. Part 5 § 5.5(e)(2). You may submit your appeal electronically at GILDFOIAAppeals@ice.dhs.gov or via regular mail to: 

U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement 
Office of the Principal Legal Advisor 
U.S. Department of Homeland Security 
500 12th Street,, S.W., Mail Stop 5900 
Washington, D.C. 20536-5900 

Your envelope and letter should be marked “FOIA Appeal.”  Copies of the FOIA and DHS regulations are available at www.dhs.gov/foia. 

ICE has queried the appropriate program offices within ICE for responsive records. If any responsive records are located, they will be reviewed for determination of releasability. Please be assured that one of the processors in our office will respond to your request as expeditiously as possible. We appreciate your patience as we proceed with your request. 

If you have any questions please contact FOIA Public Liaison Daniel Edgington, at (866) 633-1182 or 500 12th St, SW Stop 5009 Washington, DC 20536-5009. Additionally, you have a right to seek dispute resolution services from the Office of Government Information Services (OGIS) which mediates disputes between FOIA requesters and Federal agencies as a non-exclusive alternative to litigation.  If you are requesting access to your own records (which is considered a Privacy Act request), you should know that OGIS does not have the authority to handle requests made under the Privacy Act of 1974.  You may contact OGIS as follows:  Office of Government Information Services, National Archives and Records Administration, 8601 Adelphi Road-OGIS, College Park, Maryland 20740-6001, e-mail at ogis@nara.gov; telephone at 202-741-5770; toll free at 1-877-684-6448. 

Your request has been assigned reference number 2025-ICFO-25068. Please use this number in future correspondence. 

Sincerely, 

ICE FOIA Office 
Immigration and Customs Enforcement 
Freedom of Information Act Office 
500 12th Street, S.W., Stop 5009 
Washington, D.C. 20536-5009

You have requested records pertaining to a copy of the IHSC Mortality Review for Jaspar Singh, who died in ICE Custody April 15, 2024, according to the Detainee Death Report ICE published: https://www.ice.gov/doclib/foia/reports/ddrSinghJaspar.pdf. ICE has considered your request under the FOIA, 5 U.S.C. § 552. 

ICE considered the foreseeable harm standard when reviewing the record set and has applied the FOIA exemptions as required by the statute and the Attorney General’s Guidance. 

A search of the ICE Offices of Enforcement and Removal Operations (ERO) and Office of Professional Responsibility (OPR) for records responsive to your request produced 8 pages that are responsive to your request.  After review of those documents, I have determined portions of 8 pages will be withheld pursuant to Exemptions of the FOIA as described below. 
ICE has applied FOIA Exemptions 6 and 7(C) to protect from disclosure the names, e-mail addresses, and phone numbers of DHS employees, as well as other third-party information contained within the documents. 

FOIA Exemption 6 exempts from disclosure personnel or medical files and similar files the release of which would cause a clearly unwarranted invasion of personal privacy.  This requires a balancing of the public’s right to disclosure against the individual’s right to privacy.  The privacy interests of the individuals in the records you have requested outweigh any minimal public interest in disclosure of the information.  Any private interest you may have in that information does not factor into the aforementioned balancing test. 

FOIA Exemption 7(C) protects records or information compiled for law enforcement purposes that could reasonably be expected to constitute an unwarranted invasion of personal privacy.  This exemption takes particular note of the strong interests of individuals, whether they are suspects, witnesses, or investigators, in not being unwarrantably associated with alleged criminal activity.  That interest extends to persons who are not only the subjects of the investigation, but those who may have their privacy invaded by having their identities and information about them revealed in connection with an investigation.  Based upon the traditional recognition of strong privacy interest in law enforcement records, categorical withholding of information that identifies third parties in law enforcement records is ordinarily appropriate.  As such, I have determined that the privacy interest in the identities of individuals in the records you have requested clearly outweigh any minimal public interest in disclosure of the information.  Please note that any private interest you may have in that information does not factor into this determination. 

You have a right to appeal the above withholding determination.  Should you wish to do so, you must send your appeal and a copy of this letter, within 90 days of the date of this letter following the procedures outlined in the DHS FOIA regulations at 6 C.F.R. Part 5 § 5.8. You may submit your appeal electronically at GILDFOIAAppeals@ice.dhs.gov or via regular mail to: 

U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement 
Office of the Principal Legal Advisor 
U.S. Department of Homeland Security 
500 12th Street, S.W., Mail Stop 5900 
Washington, D.C. 20536-5900 

Your envelope and letter should be marked “FOIA Appeal.”  Copies of the FOIA and DHS regulations are available at www.dhs.gov/foia. 

Provisions of FOIA allow DHS to charge for processing fees, up to $25, unless you seek a waiver of fees.  In this instance, because the cost is below the $25 minimum, there is no charge. 

If you have any questions, please contact FOIA Public Liaison Daniel Edgington at (866) 633-1182 or 500 12th St., SW Stop 5009 Washington, DC 20536-5009.  Additionally, you have a right to right to seek dispute resolution services from the Office of Government Information Services (OGIS) which mediates disputes between FOIA requesters and Federal agencies as a non-exclusive alternative to litigation.  If you are requesting access to your own records (which is considered a Privacy Act request), you should know that OGIS does not have the authority to handle requests made under the Privacy Act of 1974.  You may contact OGIS as follows:  Office of Government Information Services, National Archives and Records Administration, 8601 Adelphi Road-OGIS, College Park, Maryland 20740-6001, e-mail at ogis@nara.gov; telephone at 202-741-5770; toll free at 1-877-684-6448. 

Sincerely, 

Megan Davis 
Deputy FOIA Officer, Operations

communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

All files on Michael Ryan Davis, professionally known as Mike Davis, a political activist, writer, and historian who wrote frequently about California. Davis lived March 10, 1946 – October 25, 2022, and his death was widely reported in the media.

https://www.npr.org/2022/10/26/1131578207/writer-truck-driver-meatcutter-and-prophet-of-compassion-mike-davis-dies-at-76

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Jacob Silverman

Thank you for contacting foipaquestions@fbi.gov.  Please check the status of your FOIPA Request at http://vault.fbi.gov by clicking on “Check Status of Your FOI/PA Request” on the right side of the page, and follow the instructions below.

Check the Status of Your FOIPA Request
If your FOIPA Number is [1234567-0] please enter [1234567-000] into the system. If your FOIPA Number is [1234567-1] please enter [1234567-001] into the system. If you have any questions about the status of your FOIPA request, please e-mail foipaquestions@fbi.gov.

FIND STATUS OF FOIPA- Request statuses are updated weekly

Please enter the whole FOIPA number-Example: [1234567-000]

FOIPA:
Results will show the Request Number, Case Type and Process Description shown below:
FOIPA:
1234567-000

Case Type:
FOIPA

Process Description (Will display the current progress of the request)
The FBI’s FOIPA Program is searching the FBI’s indices for potentially responsive documents.
You may be contacted via formal letter for all fees and/or negotiation issues that may apply.

NOTE: Recent requests are entered into the FOIPA database in the order that they are received. Before you can check the status, you must have received correspondence assigning a FOIPA request number and the information transferred to the online database. Status information is updated weekly. If a request has been closed within the last six months the online database will display the following: The FOIPA number entered has been closed, and appropriate correspondence has been sent to the address on file.

Estimated Dates of Completion
Requests are processed in the order in which they are received through our multi-track processing system.  Requests are divided into two primary tracks--simple (under 50 pages of potentially responsive documents) and complex (over 50 pages of potentially responsive documents).  Complex requests are further divided into medium, large, and extra-large sub-tracks based upon request size.  Simple track requests typically require the least amount of time to process.  Currently, simple track cases average approximately 122 days from the date of receipt for processing.  Our complex requests in the medium processing track are currently averaging 1,230 days, large processing track are currently averaging approximately 2,010 days, and extra-large processing track are currently averaging 2,370 days for processing.

Respectfully,

Public Information Officer
FBI - Information Management Division
200 Constitution Drive
Winchester, VA  22602

Please check the status of your request online at https://vault.fbi.gov/fdps-1/@@search-fdps    Status updates are performed on a weekly basis.

Note:  This is a non-emergency email address.  If this is an emergency, please call 911 directly.  If you need to report a tip for immediate action, please contact FBI Tips at http://tips.fbi.gov/ or reach out to your local field office.

communications.subject: Pennsylvania Right to Know Act Request: 911 Police Dispatch
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Pennsylvania Right to Know Act, I hereby request the following records:

1. An accounting of all calls for service (sometimes referred to as "dispatch logs") between the dates of 1/1/20 and 1/31/25. Please provide these in the format in which they are stored in your system, which may be a database, spreadsheet, CSV file, or similar. The format may also be the same as Allegheny County’s 911 dispatches for EMS and Fire, which are published to WPRDC: https://data.wprdc.org/dataset/allegheny-county-911-dispatches-ems-and-fire
The database may include, but not be limited to, properties relating to: call date and time; origin of the call (police-initiated, 911 call, 311 call, etc.); who was dispatched; call disposition; call resolution time.
2. A data dictionary describing the properties present in the table, and how they relate to other records such as published incidents or arrests.
3. Any additional training materials or documentation for how this data is created, or how it should be used internally.

If any part of the request cannot be met, please proceed with the remaining parts.

If any part of the request is denied, please cite the law under which the denial is allowed.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Josh Chamberlain

communications.subject: RE: Pennsylvania Right to Know Act Request #W019438-022325
communications.communication:
Hi Kathy,

I have received the flash drive. Thank you for putting it together! I have a couple followup questions which may save the trouble of an additional request:

The drive consists of 5 PDFs over 120MB and 75,000 pages each. This is not a usable database format, and would require significant effort to parse and use—as not to mention the reality of error in conversion. I had originally requested that the records be shared in the same format in which you have them stored, i.e. a database.  Would your office be able to export this data into a more usable format? CSV, JSON, Excel, SQLite? 

Additionally, it's not possible to determine whether each call was a police, fire, or EMS response. The data dictionary from WPRDC for the Fire/EMS dispatch is similar, but not applicable. Is there an explanation of the "call type" property which may shed some light, or a property which documents who was dispatched?

Thank you,
Josh

Targets are defined as paper and metal targets used by the department for shooting lethal and nonlethal weapons (40mm foam rounds, tasers, etc). They can be stationary or moving.

communications.subject: Texas Public Information Act Request: Settlement agreement in Jackson v. Wright
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Texas Public Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Any settlement agreement in Jackson v. Wright, No. 4:21-cv-00033-ALM in the U.S. District Court for the Eastern District of Texas.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Adam Steinbaugh

title: Number and impact of data center customers (Benton County Public Utility District)

communications.subject: Washington Public Records Act Request: Number and impact of data center customers (Benton County Public Utility District)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Washington Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

1. Number of Data Center Customers - The total number of customers categorized as "data centers" or equivalent from January 1, 2019, to the present, broken down by year.
2. Electricity Consumption - The total electricity consumption (in kilowatt-hours or megawatt-hours) attributed to data center customers for each year from January 1, 2019, to the present.
3. Growth of Data Center Customers - Year-over-year growth (in terms of number and consumption) of data center customers from January 1, 2019, to the present.
4. Internal Communications - All internal communications, including emails, meeting minutes, memos, and reports, related to policies, plans, or discussions on serving data center customers, dated from January 1, 2019, to the present.
5. Policies and Guidelines - Any official or draft policies, guidelines, or procedures created, revised, or implemented since January 1, 2019, that address the operation, service rates, or requirements for data center customers.

To assist in processing this request, I am specifically interested in documents, communications, or data related to:
- Power usage and billing structures for data center customers.
- Discussions on accommodating the growth of data centers in the service area.
- Environmental and infrastructure impact considerations related to data center customers.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Robin Monks

     *   Benton PUD does not provide service to any customers categorized as “data centers”.

     *   Benton PUD does not provide service to any data centers.
  2.  Growth of Data Center Customers - Year-over-year growth (in terms of number and consumption) of data center customers from January 1, 2019, to the present.
     *   Benton PUD does not provide service to any data centers.

This records request is still open and you will receive another installment of records.

title: Eltife and Rathgerber text messages with Robert Black

communications.subject: Texas Public Information Act Request: Eltife and Rathgerber text messages with Robert Black
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Texas Public Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Any emails, text messages, or other one-to-one or one-to-many forms of communication between either Kevin Eltife or Julia Rathgerber, on the one hand, and Robert Black, on the other. This request is limited to emails or text messages on or after January 1, 2025. This request is not (and can not be) limited based on subject matter or keyword.

Please note that this request seeks public records wherever they may be found, including on devices or networks owned or operated by private parties. title: Surveillance technology procured by VA law enforcement agencies

communications.subject: Virginia Freedom of Information Act Request: Surveillance technology procured by VA law enforcement agencies
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Virginia Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

The Department of Criminal Justice Services (DCJS) Summary Report on Surveillance Technology Equipment Procured by Virginia Law Enforcement Agencies, 2024, https://www.dcjs.virginia.gov/sites/dcjs.virginia.gov/files/publications/research/summary-report-surveillance-technology-equipment-procured-virginia-law-enforcement-agencies-2024.pdf, notes that 275 law enforcement agencies reported on their acquisition of surveillance tech equipment. The Summary Report contains tables describing their responses.

I would like to learn what tech each of the 275 agencies have acquired.

Please provide any logs, lists, reports and the underlying data sets that describe the names of the individual agencies and each tech item the agency has procured.  

If the logs, lists, reports and the underlying data sets are not extant, please provide copies of the completed reporting forms from each of the 275 agencies.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Tom Nash, a citizen of Virginia, in coordination with Paul Tepper.

This office is in receipt of your request for records made in accordance with the Virginia Freedom of Information Act (§2.2-3700 et seq.), which was received on July 23, 2025, where you are requesting "Information regarding DCJS' Summary Report on Surveillance Technology Equipment Procured by Virginia Law Enforcement Agencies, 2024, and what technologies each of the agencies in the report have acquired."
Attached please find documents responsive to your request.


Laureen Hyman
Assistant to the Director
Virginia Department of Criminal Justice Services
1100 Bank Street, Richmond, VA 23219
(804) 786-8718   Fax: (804) 786-0588
www.dcjs.virginia.gov<../../../ijr24809/Documents/www.dcjs.virginia.gov>

For up to date information, subscribe to DCJS Updates:  www.dcjs.virginia.gov/subscribe<http://www.dcjs.virginia.gov/subscribe>
Visit us on Facebook: www.facebook.com/vadcjs<https://www.facebook.com/vadcjs> and Flickr: www.flickr.com/photos/va_dcjs<http://www.flickr.com/photos/va_dcjs/>

CONFIDENTIALITY NOTICE:
The contents of this email message and any attachments are intended solely for the addressee(s) and may contain confidential and/or privileged information and may be legally protected from disclosure. If you are not the intended recipient of this message or their agent, or if this message has been addressed to you in error, please immediately alert the sender by reply email and then delete this message and any attachments. If you are not the intended recipient, you are hereby notified that any use, dissemination, copying, or storage of this message or its attachments is strictly prohibited.

title: Graffiti Nuisance Notices

communications.subject: Washington Public Records Act Request: Graffiti Nuisance Notices
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Washington Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

1. The spreadsheet of all graffiti nuisance notices issued by the city since 9/1/24. Please refer to the records you provided in response to my previous request C192645-080824.
2. A copy of the most recent graffiti nuisance notice issued.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Rose Terse

title: Bruce Harrell's Anarchists

communications.subject: Washington Public Records Act Request: Bruce Harrell's Anarchists
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Washington Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

According to KING5, Mayor Harrell claimed that "anarchists joined the counterprotesters, which resulted in violence and arrests".
https://www.king5.com/article/news/local/seattle-police-arrests-cal-anderson-park-protest/281-66330e3a-ae65-4076-a919-12e2d89c50e2

Please provide any documents, communications (including but not limited to text messages), or other memoranda from May 24, 2025 mentioning anarchists including attachments and associated metadata.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Rose Terse

communications.communication:
Good morning,

The University of Nebraska has received and assessed your below public records request. Upon review, the University declines to provide records responsive to your request. The University has reviewed the request and determined that the records requested are not subject to disclosure under the Nebraska Public Records Act, based upon the exception contained in Neb. Rev. Stat. § 84-712.05(1). The University also declines to provide records pursuant to the Family Educational Rights and Privacy Act (FERPA), 20 USC § 1232g. The University has determined that any nonexempt material is not reasonably segregable from materials not subject to disclosure under Neb. Rev. Stat. § 84-712.05(1) and FERPA. See Neb. Rev. Stat. § 84-712.06.

I am the public official responsible for the decision to deny this request for the reasons stated above. You can challenge that decision as outlined in Neb. Rev. The University of Nebraska’s four campuses – University of Nebraska Omaha, University of Nebraska at Kearney, University of Nebraska-Lincoln, and University of Nebraska Medical Center each track these numbers separately, and University of Nebraska Medical Center (UNMC) tracks numbers differently than the other three campuses, as explained below.

The numbers requested for University of Nebraska Omaha, University of Nebraska at Kearney, and University of Nebraska-Lincoln are as follows:

2021-22: 25

Case Type

AY 2021-2022

AY 2023-2024

AY 2024-2025

Academic Integrity

238

162

203

216



Upon review, the University has not identified a record for UNMC showing aggregate annual data as requested. UNMC does not maintain a report showing annual report totals or totals by college. George Smith

George Smith

title: Silvio Berlusconi

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Silvio Berlusconi
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Records mentioning, relating to, or generated as a result of investigation or inquiry into former Italian prime minister Silvio Berlusconi (29 September 1936 – 12 June 2023). His death is widely-known and has been widely reported, privacy concerns under FOIA Exemptions 6 and 7 are voided, as are any concerns under the Privacy Act. For example, see the following BBC article: https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-65877241

Please conduct a search of the Central Records System, including but not limited to the Electronic Surveillance (ELSUR) Indices, the Microphone Surveillance (MISUR) Indices, the Physical Surveillance (FISUR) Indices, and the Technical Surveillance (TESUR) Indices, for both main-file records and cross-reference records of both HQ and all field offices for all relevant names, agencies, organizations, companies and events including but not limited to those cited in the previous paragraphs and/or links as well as a cross-reference with the Southern Poverty Law Center to include any information provided by the SPLC. My request includes but is not limited to 137, 157, 176, 177, 183, 184, 188, and 214 files.

If any part of these documents are exempt from disclosure, please be sure to review and release all reasonably segregable nonexempt portions of responsive documents, as the FOIA requires

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Matthew Petti

communications.subject: RE: [EXTERNAL EMAIL] -  RE: Freedom of Information Act Request #1596158-000
communications.communication:
Thank you for contacting foipaquestions@fbi.gov.  Please check the status of your FOIPA Request at http://vault.fbi.gov by clicking on “Check Status of Your FOI/PA Request” on the right side of the page, and follow the instructions below.

Check the Status of Your FOIPA Request
If your FOIPA Number is [1234567-0] please enter [1234567-000] into the system. If your FOIPA Number is [1234567-1] please enter [1234567-001] into the system. If you have any questions about the status of your FOIPA request, please e-mail foipaquestions@fbi.gov.

FIND STATUS OF FOIPA- Request statuses are updated weekly

Please enter the whole FOIPA number-Example: [1234567-000]

FOIPA:
Results will show the Request Number, Case Type and Process Description shown below:
FOIPA:
1234567-000

Case Type:
FOIPA

Process Description (Will display the current progress of the request)
The FBI’s FOIPA Program is searching the FBI’s indices for potentially responsive documents.
You may be contacted via formal letter for all fees and/or negotiation issues that may apply.

NOTE: Recent requests are entered into the FOIPA database in the order that they are received. Before you can check the status, you must have received correspondence assigning a FOIPA request number and the information transferred to the online database. Status information is updated weekly. If a request has been closed within the last six months the online database will display the following: The FOIPA number entered has been closed, and appropriate correspondence has been sent to the address on file.

Estimated Dates of Completion
Requests are processed in the order in which they are received through our multi-track processing system.  Requests are divided into two primary tracks--simple (under 50 pages of potentially responsive documents) and complex (over 50 pages of potentially responsive documents).  Complex requests are further divided into medium, large, and extra-large sub-tracks based upon request size.  Simple track requests typically require the least amount of time to process.  Currently, simple track cases average approximately 122 days from the date of receipt for processing.  Our complex requests in the medium processing track are currently averaging 1,230 days, large processing track are currently averaging approximately 2,010 days, and extra-large processing track are currently averaging 2,370 days for processing.

Respectfully,

Public Information Officer
FBI - Information Management Division
200 Constitution Drive
Winchester, VA  22602
O: (540) 868-4593
E: foipaquestions@fbi.gov<mailto:foipaquestions@fbi.gov>

Do you have further questions about the FOI/PA process? Visit us at http://www.fbi.gov/foia

Please check the status of your request online at https://vault.fbi.gov/fdps-1/@@search-fdps    Status updates are performed on a weekly basis.

Note:  This is a non-emergency email address.  If this is an emergency, please call 911 directly.  If you need to report a tip for immediate action, please contact FBI Tips at http://tips.fbi.gov/ or reach out to your local field office.

communications.subject: Mississippi Public Records Act Request: Untitled
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Mississippi Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

Dear Records Officer,

Pursuant to the Mississippi Public Records Act (Miss. Code Ann. § 25-61-1 et seq.), I am requesting access to and copies of the following non-privileged digital forensic records generated by the DeSoto County Sheriff’s Department in relation to a Cellebrite digital extraction conducted on or around January 2, 2019 involving a laptop and/or digital storage media seized from David Hunter Moore (DOB: April, 28, 1995 , Case No: CR2019-0392GCD).

To be clear, I am not requesting access to any images or video content of an explicit nature, nor to any alleged child sexual abuse material. This request is limited to the technical, metadata, and extraction-related logs and reports generated by Cellebrite or similar forensic tools. Specifically, I am requesting:

⸻

Requested Items:
    1.    Cellebrite UFED Extraction Reports
    •    Any full or partial .ufdr, .xml, .html, or .pdf reports generated during analysis.
    •    These reports include structured output of file system artifacts, timestamps, user activity, and metadata.
    2.    Cellebrite-generated Artifact and Activity Logs
    •    Including file system logs, user action logs (viewed/opened files), cloud sync reports, and app usage timelines.
    3.    Hash Value Logs and Verification Tables
    •    SHA1/SHA256 hash logs for digital files located on any seized device, including CSV or text file outputs.
    4.    Chain of Custody Logs Related to Cellebrite Imaging
    •    Any logs indicating the date/time of imaging, name of operator, device serial number, and actions taken.
    5.    Device Information Summary Reports
    •    Basic device identification info (make/model/serial), OS version, and extraction summary.
    6.    File Path Trees and Artifact Maps
    •    Reports showing directory structure and file placement (including synced folders such as Dropbox, if present).

⸻

Format & Delivery:

Please provide the above records in electronic format (email or digital media). I am willing to pay reasonable duplication fees in accordance with Mississippi law. If any part of this request is denied, please provide the legal basis for the denial in writing and redact only those portions which are exempt while releasing the remainder.

⸻

Urgency & Public Interest:

This request is made in the public interest and for the purpose of investigating potential forensic irregularities in digital evidence handling and attribution. Given the potential implications for due process rights and forensic accuracy, prompt disclosure is requested.

Please respond within the 7 business days required by statute. If you require clarification, feel free to contact me directly at mikegrey@outlook.com.

Sincerely,

Michael GreY

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 7 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Marlon

communications.subject: Wyoming Public Records Act Request: wyoming board license list
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Wyoming Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

1. Complete Current Licensee Database
A comprehensive list of all currently licensed medical professionals in Wyoming, including:

Physicians (MD)
Doctors of Osteopathic Medicine (DO)
Physician Assistants (PA)
Any other medical professionals under Board jurisdiction

For each licensee, please provide:

License number
Full name
License type/designation
Current license status
Initial license date
License expiration date

2. Disciplinary Action Records
For each current licensee listed above, please indicate:

Whether any disciplinary action has ever been taken by the Board
Type of disciplinary action(s) taken (if any)
Date(s) of disciplinary action(s)
Case/docket numbers for disciplinary proceedings
Current status of any ongoing disciplinary matters

Clarification and Scope

This request seeks only records pertaining to current, active licensees
All requested information constitutes public records under Wyoming law
Disciplinary actions are already publicly disclosed on the Board's website; this request seeks the same information in a comprehensive, searchable format
No protected health information or confidential records are being requested
Personal contact information (addresses, phone numbers) may be redacted if deemed necessary

Format and Delivery
I would prefer to receive these records electronically via email attachment in Excel or CSV format if possible, or on CD-ROM if electronic delivery is not available.
In the event that there are fees associated with this request, please inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling the request.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 7 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Vig Sinclair

title: Texas universities: Past and planned student events (University Of Texas Arlington)

communications.subject: Texas Public Information Act Request: Texas universities: Past and planned student events (University Of Texas Arlington)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Texas Public Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

This is a survey of events planned or proposed by recognized or registered student organizations (or individual students or faculty members). I am seeking copies of calendar entries for events that were held or proposed. I am not seeking a search of records held by students or student organizations. I am only seeking information held by the university administration (for example, in an Event Management System, which may be helpful in providing a list of past events and proposed future events). 

If this request is unclear or if I could clarify it in any way, please don't hesitate to ask.

I request:

1. All calendar entries (or Event Management System database entries) for events held or sponsored by a registered student organization, individual student, or faculty member during the final two weeks of each term during 2023, 2024, and Winter/Spring 2025. If your institution's academic calendar does not identify a final date of a given term, please use the final day of exams for the term as the final day of the term.

2. All calendar entries (or Event Management System database entries) for events held or sponsored by a registered student organization, individual student, or faculty member after 10:00 p.m. and/or before 8:00 a.m., between January 31, 2023 and July 1, 2025.

3. All calendar entries for events which are or were proposed to be held by a registered student organization, individual student, or faculty member, where the event is proposed to be held after 10:00 p.m. and/or before 8:00 a.m. This request is limited to events that are proposed to be held between July 1, 2025 and July 1, 2026. 

4. All calendar entries for events which are or were proposed to be held by a registered student organization, individual student, or faculty member, where the event is proposed to be during the final two weeks of a term in the Fall 2025, Winter 2025-2026, or Spring 2026 semesters/terms. Please us the same means of calculating "final two weeks" as in (1), above.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Adam Steinbaugh

communications.subject: RE: Texas Public Information Act Request #PIR-2025-416
communications.communication:
Good morning --

I'm writing with respect to a public records request sent on June 27, 2025. I understand that the university responded to a different request (which sought information about a lacrosse coach) in Request No. PIR-2025-416. However, my request is different. It sought:

This is a survey of events planned or proposed by recognized or registered student organizations (or individual students or faculty members). I am seeking copies of calendar entries for events that were held or proposed. I am not seeking a search of records held by students or student organizations. I am only seeking information held by the university administration (for example, in an Event Management System, which may be helpful in providing a list of past events and proposed future events).

If this request is unclear or if I could clarify it in any way, please don't hesitate to ask.

I request:

1. All calendar entries (or Event Management System database entries) for events held or sponsored by a registered student organization, individual student, or faculty member during the final two weeks of each term during 2023, 2024, and Winter/Spring 2025. If your institution's academic calendar does not identify a final date of a given term, please use the final day of exams for the term as the final day of the term.

2. All calendar entries (or Event Management System database entries) for events held or sponsored by a registered student organization, individual student, or faculty member after 10:00 p.m. and/or before 8:00 a.m., between January 31, 2023 and July 1, 2025.

3. All calendar entries for events which are or were proposed to be held by a registered student organization, individual student, or faculty member, where the event is proposed to be held after 10:00 p.m. and/or before 8:00 a.m. This request is limited to events that are proposed to be held between July 1, 2025 and July 1, 2026.

4. All calendar entries for events which are or were proposed to be held by a registered student organization, individual student, or faculty member, where the event is proposed to be during the final two weeks of a term in the Fall 2025, Winter 2025-2026, or Spring 2026 semesters/terms. Please us the same means of calculating "final two weeks" as in (1), above.

Thank you,

Adam Steinbaugh

title: Information Relating to the Selection and Performance of Third Party Parking Vendors (City Of Mukilteo)

communications.subject: Washington Public Records Act Request: Information Relating to the Selection and Performance of Third Party Parking Vendors (City Of Mukilteo)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Washington Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

I request copies of all records related to the City of Mukilteo's third-party parking vendors (such as those providing payment, license place readers, ticket printers, signage, parking studies, mobile applications like Passport) from January 1, 2020, to the present date. Specifically, I am requesting:

1.    All documents related to the Request for Proposal (RFP) process for parking management services, including:
a.        Initial RFP drafts and final published documents
b.       Evaluation criteria used to assess vendor proposals
c.        Meeting minutes from selection committee discussions
d.        Scoring sheets or decision matrices used in the vendor selection process
2.    All vendor responses or applications to parking management RFPs, including proposals for:
a.        Parking management software and applications
b.        Parking signage systems and solutions
 c.       Enforcement tools (specifically ticket printers and license plate recognition technology)
3.    All contracts, agreements, amendments, and memoranda of understanding with selected parking vendors
4.    All internal communications, emails, memos, and meeting notes regarding:
a.        The selection process for parking vendors
b.        Implementation of parking management systems
c.        Performance evaluations of parking vendors
d.        Any issues or concerns raised about vendor performance
5.    Financial records related to payments made to parking vendors, including invoices and payment records
6.    Any studies, reports, or assessments related to parking management or enforcement conducted by or for the City of Mukilteo since 2020

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Robin Monks

I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not. Pursuant to RCW 42.56.520(1)(c), the City is notifying you that it needs additional time to respond to your request. This additional time is necessary to locate records that may be responsive to your request and, if responsive records are located, determine whether any exemptions might apply to those records. Please be advised that we may also need to notify third parties of this request before we disclose certain records. Consequently, the City will respond to your request on an installment basis pursuant to RCW 42.56.080. Our initial estimate is that the first installment of the records, if existing, may be available on June 13, 2025. This anticipated date is only an estimate, which may need to be revised as we process your request. If you have any questions or would like to discuss this request further, please feel free to contact me at clerk@mukilteowa.gov. Respectfully, Asea Sandine City Clerk 11930 Cyrus Way • Mukilteo, Washington 98275 • 425-263-8005 • www.Mukilteowa.gov (www.Mukilteowa.gov)

Robin Monks

Boston MA 02115 RE: Public Records Request: P000679-051325 Dear Robin Monks, We are writing to update you on the status of your public records request.  Please be advised that due to the scope of your request, it is our experience that requests of this nature generally take longer to complete.  In this instance, we currently estimate that the City's response may be completed by July 10, 2025. Please note that this is only an estimate and may be subject to change as the City works on the response to your request. In an effort to provide the fullest assistance in processing your request, the City will produce identified records in installments as records become available.  Accordingly, an installment of records is now available for you to review and download at the City's records portal which you can access by following the steps below:  
  * Begin clicking here
  * Select the link to "View My Public Records Requests." 
  * Click “View my requests." 
  * Log in. 
  * Click “View Files” and the responsive records will be available to download as a link at the top of the page. The City of Mukilteo requires additional time to continue processing your request. We believe that another installment will be available on or about 7/10/2025.  We will provide you with a status report on or before that date. Should you have any questions, please feel free to respond to this email through your portal account or call the City Clerk’s office at 425-263-8005.   07/10/2025 Robin Monks 
MuckRock News, DEPT MR186339 263 Huntington Ave 
Boston MA 02115 RE: Public Records Request dated: 5/13/2025; P000679-051325 Dear Robin Monks, We are writing to update you on the status of your public records request.  In accordance with RCW 42.56.520(2) The City of Mukilteo requires additional time to locate, review or redact records responsive to your request. At this time we believe that records responsive to your request will be available on or about 7/24/2025, and we will provide you with a status report on or before that date. Should you have any questions, please feel free to respond to this email or call the City Clerk’s office at 425-263-8005. Respectfully, Asea Sandine City Clerk 11930 Cyrus Way • Mukilteo, Washington 98275 • 425-263-8005 • www.Mukilteowa.gov (www.Mukilteowa.gov)

communications.subject: Police Records Request :: P000679-051325
communications.communication:
--- Please respond above this line --- 

   
  07/24/2025 Robin Monks 
MuckRock News, DEPT MR186339 263 Huntington Ave 
Boston MA 02115 RE: Public Records Request: P000679-051325 Dear Robin Monks, We are writing to update you as to the status of your above-referenced records request. Following a reasonable search, the City has completed the assembly an installment of responsive records to your request, pursuant to the Washington State Public Records Act, Chapter 42.56 RCW. Below is an itemized list of fees incurred: Scanned page $0.10 The charges for the records total $0.10 You may make your payment via the portal, in person at the Mukilteo City Hall cashier desk located at  11930 Cyrus Way, Mukilteo, WA 98033, during regular business hours which are Monday through Thursday 8:00a.m. to 5:00p.m. Alternatively, you may mail a check to the above address, and following receipt of payment, the City will release the records via the City's Records Portal upon payment, according to the preference you have indicated. Your check should be made out to the City of Mukilteo and addressed to the City Clerk’s Office at the address above.  Please include your reference number in the memo section of your check. Should you have any questions, please feel free to respond to this email through your portal account or call the City Clerk’s Office at 425-263-8005. Respectfully, Asea Sandine City Clerk 11930 Cyrus Way  •  Mukilteo, Washington 98275  •  425.263-8005  • www.Mukilteowa.gov

  07/28/2025 Robin Monks 
MuckRock News, DEPT MR186339 263 Huntington Ave 
Boston MA 02115 RE: Police Records Request of May 13, 2025, Reference # P000679-051325 Dear Robin Monks, The City received a public records request from you on May 13, 2025. Your request mentioned: To Whom It May Concern: 

Pursuant to the Washington Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records: 

I request copies of all records related to the City of Mukilteo's third-party parking vendors (such as those providing payment, license place readers, ticket printers, signage, parking studies, mobile applications like Passport) from January 1, 2020, to the present date. Specifically, I am requesting: 

1. All documents related to the Request for Proposal (RFP) process for parking management services, including: 
a. Initial RFP drafts and final published documents 
b. Evaluation criteria used to assess vendor proposals 
c. Meeting minutes from selection committee discussions 
d. Scoring sheets or decision matrices used in the vendor selection process 
2. All vendor responses or applications to parking management RFPs, including proposals for: 
a. Parking management software and applications 
b. Parking signage systems and solutions 
c. Enforcement tools (specifically ticket printers and license plate recognition technology) 
3. All contracts, agreements, amendments, and memoranda of understanding with selected parking vendors 
4. All internal communications, emails, memos, and meeting notes regarding: 
a. The selection process for parking vendors 
b. Implementation of parking management systems 
c. Performance evaluations of parking vendors 
d. Any issues or concerns raised about vendor performance 
5. Financial records related to payments made to parking vendors, including invoices and payment records 
6. Any studies, reports, or assessments related to parking management or enforcement conducted by or for the City of Mukilteo since 2020 

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes. 

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not. 

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires. 

Sincerely, 

Robin Monks

communications.communication:
--- Please respond above this line --- 

   
  07/28/2025 Robin Monks 
MuckRock News, DEPT MR186339 263 Huntington Ave 
Boston MA 02115 RE: Fulfillment of Public Records Request: P000679-051325 Dear Robin Monks, We are writing to update you as to the status of your above-referenced records request.  The City has completed its search and uploaded records identified as responsive to your request to the City's records portal which you can access by following the steps below:  
  *  Begin by clicking here. 
  *  Select the link to "View My Public Records Requests." 
  *  Click “View my requests." 
  *  Log in. 
  *  Click “View Files” and the responsive records will be available to download as a link at the top of the page. Due to glitches with invoicing the invoice was voided and identifiable documents were released and available in the portal. A link was provided for the November 4, 2024 City Council Meeting - Agenda item 8 (AB24-166) to satisfy item 6 of your request. At this time, the City believes it has fulfilled your request and will close the above-referenced request file.  If staff has misinterpreted any part of your request, please advise as soon as possible, as it is the intent of staff to fully comply with RCW 42.56 in a timely manner. Please note that staff do not routinely monitor closed requests. This serves as the agency's final response, and your request has been closed. The City does not plan to provide further responses, and the one-year statute of limitations has commenced. For any questions or concerns regarding this request, feel free to reach out to me at clerk@mukilteowa.gov or 425-263-8005. Any questions you raise will not extend the final closing date of this request. (mailto:clerk@mukilteowa.gov) Respectfully, Asea Sandine City Clerk 11930 Cyrus Way  •  Mukilteo, Washington 98275  •  425.263-8005  • www.Mukilteowa.gov

Matthew Fecteau

title: Texas universities: Past and planned student events (Lamar University)

communications.subject: Texas Public Information Act Request: Texas universities: Past and planned student events (Lamar University)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Texas Public Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

This is a survey of events planned or proposed by recognized or registered student organizations (or individual students or faculty members). I am seeking copies of calendar entries for events that were held or proposed. I am not seeking a search of records held by students or student organizations. I am only seeking information held by the university administration (for example, in an Event Management System, which may be helpful in providing a list of past events and proposed future events). 

If this request is unclear or if I could clarify it in any way, please don't hesitate to ask.

I request:

1. All calendar entries (or Event Management System database entries) for events held or sponsored by a registered student organization, individual student, or faculty member during the final two weeks of each term during 2023, 2024, and Winter/Spring 2025. If your institution's academic calendar does not identify a final date of a given term, please use the final day of exams for the term as the final day of the term.

2. All calendar entries (or Event Management System database entries) for events held or sponsored by a registered student organization, individual student, or faculty member after 10:00 p.m. and/or before 8:00 a.m., between January 31, 2023 and July 1, 2025.

3. All calendar entries for events which are or were proposed to be held by a registered student organization, individual student, or faculty member, where the event is proposed to be held after 10:00 p.m. and/or before 8:00 a.m. This request is limited to events that are proposed to be held between July 1, 2025 and July 1, 2026. 

4. All calendar entries for events which are or were proposed to be held by a registered student organization, individual student, or faculty member, where the event is proposed to be during the final two weeks of a term in the Fall 2025, Winter 2025-2026, or Spring 2026 semesters/terms. Please us the same means of calculating "final two weeks" as in (1), above.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Adam Steinbaugh

title: Request on Political Appointees (Office of National Drug Control Policy)

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Request on Political Appointees (Office of National Drug Control Policy)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

This is a request under the Freedom of Information Act. I hereby request the following records:

1. A list of any and all political appointments at the agency appointed from January 20, 2025 until the date of your final response to this request.

2. Copies of resumes for any and all political appointees hired since January 20, 2025 until the date of your final response to this request. These records are likely in the possession of the Designated Agency Ethics Official (DAEO).

Please provide these records as available on a rolling basis.

Documented is an investigative watchdog and reporting group that explores the relationship between special interests and government. This request is likely to contribute significantly to the public’s understanding of the operations of the government. Disclosure of the requested records serves the public interest, and this request is not being made for any commercial purposes. Therefore, I am requesting a waiver of any fees. If you do not grant my fee waiver request, please notify me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request be filled electronically by email attachment or other electronic file transfer if available, or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter.  I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,
Nina
