title: Use of force (response to resistance) guidance, policies, and data (St Michaels Police Department FOIA)

communications.subject: Maryland Public Information Act Request: Use of force (response to resistance) guidance, policies, and data (St Michaels Police Department FOIA)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Maryland Public Information Act, I hereby request the following records related to this agency's policies on and reporting of uses of force and responses to resistance:

• Policies. 
Any and all policies guiding appropriate and inappropriate uses of force by any member or representative of this agency. These may also include “Response to Resistance” policies and similar guidance.

Please also provide all policies regarding the use of lethal, less-lethal, and non-lethal weapons (for example: TASERs pepper ball guns, rubber bullets, gases, sprays, water, etc.), including all policies regarding borrowing, accessing, or assuming responsibility for such weapons,  tools, and ammunition. 

Please also provide all policies or guidance related to reporting or tracking discharges from or uses of such weapons, as well as any other applicable policies or directives related to the acquisition, use, and reporting of weapons or tools. 

Please also provide all policies and guidance used to evaluate any use of force or adjudicate administrative and internal investigations into any use of force or weapon discharge.

• Instructions for reporting. Any and all instructions and guidance related to the reporting of uses of force by any member or representative of this agency.

• Forms, coding descriptions, and other guidance.
All forms, codes, guides, and guidance used in the reporting and review of uses of force or weapons, including:
Any list of codes or definitions for terms or tags used in the reporting, collection, or review of uses of force. 
A blank version of each form, log, and other documentation used to report or track uses of force by this agency.  
A blank version of each form, log, and other documentation used to report or track the borrowing or use of lethal, less-lethal, and non-lethal weapons
A blank version of each form, log, and other documentation used to report or track any discharge of force from firearms, tools, or weapons employed by this agency
A copy of any guidance, requirements, laws, and policies issued by the state, including those issued as part of grant or other funding requirements, regarding this agency’s responsibilities for reportings uses of force or weapons
A copy of any guidance, requirements, laws, and policies issued by the federal government, including those issued as part of grant or other funding requirements, regarding this agency’s responsibilities for reportings uses of force or weapons

• Use of Force Data 
For the period from January 1, 2019 through December 31, 2019 and the period from January 1, 2020 through July 31, 2020, data on the each use of force by representatives of this agency, including but not limited to: 
Date, time: The date (month, day, year) and time of the incident
Location: Street address, block, and other relevant location information
Subject(s) information: race, ethnicity, national origin, age, gender, resultant or related injuries sustained or alleged, weapon type (if applicable) in the possession of each involved individual, arrests or charges associated with the incident
Officer information (for each involved officer): employee number or other unique identifier used for the officer, race, resultant or related physical injuries, patrol division, unit
Incident details: incident or other unique identification number for the use of force incident
Type of force details: a description of each type of force used
Body camera or other footage: Inventory of any video record was created of the incident and/or a copy of the captured footage from all present cameras
Disposition of investigation into the incident: The current or final status of each use of force incident, including whether challenges to the use of force were sustained or dismissed or if the incident had no or is currently under investigation
Please provide the information as a csv spreadsheet, if possible, and if not possible, please provide incident reports sufficient to show the requested data. 

• Discharge Report Data 
For the period from January 1, 2019 through December 31, 2019 and the period from January 1, 2020 through July 31, 2020, data on each discharge of a firearm and other weapons by representatives of this agency, including but not limited to: 
Date, time: The date (month, day, year) and time of the incident
Location: Street address, block, and other relevant location information
Incident description and details
Tool or weapon used, including any unique identifier or identification number
Number of discharges
Subject(s) information: race, ethnicity, national origin, age, gender, resultant or related injuries sustained or alleged, weapon type (if applicable) in the possession of each involved individual, arrests or charges associated with the incident
Officer information (for each involved officer): employee number or other unique identifier used for the officer, race, resultant or related physical injuries, patrol division, unit
Type of force details: a description of each type of force used
Disposition or status of any investigation or follow-up review of the incident
Please provide the information as a csv spreadsheet, if possible, and if not possible, please provide incident reports sufficient to show the requested data. 

If any portion of materials responsive to this request should be deemed unavailable or non-disclosable, please specifically identify the portions of the records or the specific information that is unavailable and the reason for the unavailability. 

If any portion of this request is unclear or if this request could be modified to reduce the burden of producing responsive documents or provide them more efficiently or expeditiously, please reply with a request for clarification or a proposed modification.

This request is being made by a reporter as part of a journalistic investigation. It is being submitted as part of a project to better understand uses of police force nationwide, which has been of public interest for many years and which is of particular interest to large new swaths of the public following the widely-seen death of George Floyd and the First Amendment-protected demonstrations and public discussion that have followed. There is no commercial interest in the submission of this request or the release of these records.

In the event that there are fees appropriately assessed in association with this request, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter.

I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 calendar days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Beryl Lipton

title: Obama Library: WHTV Tapes of October 21st 2010 visit to Seattle

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Obama Library: WHTV Tapes of October 21st 2010 visit to Seattle
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

White House Communications Agency video footage (WHTV content) filmed during President Obama's visit to Seattle on October 21st of 2010.

This is a request to review all footage from that day, including outtakes and rushes.

The itinerary for that day is described as followed:

Arrival at Boeing Field in Seattle
The President Meets With Seattle Family  (location: private residence)
The President Holds a Discussion on Women and the economy (location: private residence)
The President Delivers Remarks at a rally for Senator Murray (UW campus)
Departure from Seattle to San Francisco 

Of particular interest (to me) is of any video from the remarks by Obama given to the overflow crowd that gathered in the Husky Stadium end zone. I was on the rope line, and shook Obama's hand, at the overflow event that day: https://obamawhitehouse.archives.gov/the-press-office/2010/10/21/remarks-president-overflow-crowd-university-washington

It would be wonderful if these could be uploaded to the Obama Presidential Library YouTube page: https://www.youtube.com/@obamalibrary - As other similar requests have been.

Thank you for the Obama Presidential Library's commitment to transparency, and I look forward to the resolution of this request.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Robert Delaware

communications.subject: Illinois Freedom of Information Act. Request: BCHS District Residency Investigation Documents
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Illinois Freedom of Information Act., I hereby request the following records:

All documents including internal and external emails and text messages concerning reports of residency fraud involving the family of Melinda and Jestin Squires and addresses 16178 E. Franklin Rd Ewing, IL and 14425 Rescue Church Rd, Whittingon, IL.

Documents pertaining to total number of complaints of suspected residency fraud made to Benton Consolidated High School, number investigated, and adjudication status for school year 2024-2025.

Documentation of BCHS policy for investigating reports of residency fraud.

Records are of public interest to determine how reports of violation of residency laws are applied and enforced and whether there is equal application of the law with regard to public position, status, and relationship to board members.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Chris Webster

title: Texas universities: Past and planned student events (Stephen F Austin State University)

communications.subject: Texas Public Information Act Request: Texas universities: Past and planned student events (Stephen F Austin State University)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Texas Public Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

This is a survey of events planned or proposed by recognized or registered student organizations (or individual students or faculty members). I am seeking copies of calendar entries for events that were held or proposed. I am not seeking a search of records held by students or student organizations. I am only seeking information held by the university administration (for example, in an Event Management System, which may be helpful in providing a list of past events and proposed future events). 

If this request is unclear or if I could clarify it in any way, please don't hesitate to ask.

I request:

1. All calendar entries (or Event Management System database entries) for events held or sponsored by a registered student organization, individual student, or faculty member during the final two weeks of each term during 2023, 2024, and Winter/Spring 2025. If your institution's academic calendar does not identify a final date of a given term, please use the final day of exams for the term as the final day of the term.

2. All calendar entries (or Event Management System database entries) for events held or sponsored by a registered student organization, individual student, or faculty member after 10:00 p.m. and/or before 8:00 a.m., between January 31, 2023 and July 1, 2025.

3. All calendar entries for events which are or were proposed to be held by a registered student organization, individual student, or faculty member, where the event is proposed to be held after 10:00 p.m. and/or before 8:00 a.m. This request is limited to events that are proposed to be held between July 1, 2025 and July 1, 2026. 

4. All calendar entries for events which are or were proposed to be held by a registered student organization, individual student, or faculty member, where the event is proposed to be during the final two weeks of a term in the Fall 2025, Winter 2025-2026, or Spring 2026 semesters/terms. Please us the same means of calculating "final two weeks" as in (1), above.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Adam Steinbaugh

communications.subject: RE: Texas Public Information Act Request: Texas universities: Past and planned student events (Stephen F Austin State University)
communications.communication:
Good morning,

Stephen F. Austin State University is in receipt of your Public Information Act request on June 30, 2025.  Per university policy 02-108 https://www.sfasu.edu/docs/hops/02-108.pdf no events are permitted during the final two weeks of each term.

Currently the university does not have an Event Management System database or other centralized method for recording the information requested.

Organizations may reserve any space on campus that is available for reservation. It will take approximately two to three weeks for a manual search of each space on campus that is available for student reservations. If you would like to narrow your request the information may be available more quickly, please respond to this email.

The university has elected to waive its usual PIA processing fee in this instance.

Thank you,

   April Smith '02 and '19
   Director of Executive Programs and Events
   Office of the President
   Stephen F. Austin State University
   PO Box 6078, SFA Station
   Nacogdoches, TX 75962-6078
   T 936.468.4048
The views and opinions expressed in this message are my own and do not necessarily reflect the views and opinions of Stephen F. Austin State University, the University of Texas System, or its Board of Regents.

communications.subject: RE: New York Freedom of Information Law Request #23-05-237
communications.communication:
Subject: Outstanding Records Needed — FOIL #23‑05‑237 (“Live Birth Data by School District – Source Data”)

Dear Records Access Office,

Thank you for your correspondence and file deliveries of  18 March 2024 and 24 October 2024 under FOIL #23‑05‑237.  
After a detailed review, it appears that several items described in my original request are still outstanding:

1. Record‑level datasets / source data used to calculate the 2021 provisional live‑birth counts by school district;
2. Programs / logic (e.g., SAS or SQL scripts, lookup tables, data‑processing documentation) applied to create those provisional counts;
3. Any 2022 provisional school‑district birth table generated since the 2021 counts were compiled; and
4. A § 89(3)(a) completeness certification confirming that all responsive records have been produced.

Kindly advise within five (5) business days whether these materials exist and, if so, when they can be supplied in native electronic format.  
If any portion is being withheld in whole or in part, please cite each specific exemption in Public Officers Law § 87(2) that you believe justifies nondisclosure, together with the factual basis for its application.

I appreciate your continued assistance and look forward to your prompt clarification.

communications.subject: Illinois Freedom of Information Act. Request: ALPR Audit (Madison County Sheriff)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Illinois Freedom of Information Act., I hereby request the following records:

1. Organization Audit in Flock.
The report should include data logged from the period January 1, 2025, to the date this request is processed. Per Flock's documentation, the Organization Audit is available within the Insights tab and is defined as searches done within the agency.

2. Network Audit in Flock.
The report should include data logged from the period of January 1, 2025, to the date this request is processed. Per Flock's documentation, the Network Audit is available within the Insights tab and is defined as searches of the organization’s Flock network by any agency in the Flock System.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Scott Kampas

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: "Ensuring Lawful Governance" EO (Environmental Protection Agency)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

The February 19 executive order  “Ensuring Lawful Governance and Implementing the President’s “Department of Government Efficiency” Deregulatory Initiative” (EO 14219) states: “Within 60 days of the date of this order, agency heads shall provide to the Administrator of the Office of Information and Regulatory Affairs (OIRA) within the Office of Management and Budget a list of all regulations identified by class as listed in subsection (a) of this section.”

https://www.federalregister.gov/documents/2025/02/25/2025-03138/ensuring-lawful-governance-and-implementing-the-presidents-department-of-government-efficiency

I am requesting the memo or reports created in response to this order, including any media and attachments sent from the Environmental Protection Agency to OIRA.

I am a member of the press, and the documents will be used in the course of reporting for Chemical Watch News & Insight (https://www.enhesa.com/product-intelligence/our-solutions/chemical-watch-news-insight/).

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Meg Duff

communications.subject: Acknowledgement of FOIA Request CBP-2019-068720
communications.communication:
C J Ciaramella 
MuckRock News, DEPT MR 77582 
411A Highland Ave 
Somerville, MA, 02144 
07/20/2019 
CBP-2019-068720 
Dear C J Ciaramella: 
This notice acknowledges receipt of your Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) request to U.S. Customs and Border Protection (CBP) received on 07/18/2019 requesting the following: 
- Any communications to or from Border Patrol Chief Carla Provost containing "Facebook", "ProPublica", "The intercept", or "I'm 10-15" between July 1, 2019 and July 17, 2019. 
- Any communications to or from current acting CBP commissioner Mark Morgan containing "I'm 10-15" between Aug. 1, 2016 and July 17, 2019. 
Please use the following unique FOIA tracking number CBP-2019-068720 to track the status of your request.  If you have not already done so, you must create a FOIAonline account at https://foiaonline.gov.  This is the only method available to check the status of your pending FOIA request. (https://foiaonline.regulations.gov/) 
Provisions of the Act allow us to recover part of the cost of complying with your request.  We shall charge you for records in accordance with the DHS FOIA regulations outlined on the DHS website, https://www.federalregister.gov/documents/2016/11/22/2016-28095/freedom-of-information-act-regulations. By submitting your request, you have agreed to pay up to $25.00 in applicable processing fees, if any fees associated with your request exceed this amount, CBP shall contact you; however, the first 100 pages are free. (https://www.federalregister.gov/documents/2016/11/22/2016-28095/freedom-of-information-act-regulations) 
Due to the increasing number of FOIA requests received by this office, we may encounter some delay in processing your request.  Consistent with 6 C.F.R. Part 5 § 5.5(a) of the DHS FOIA regulations, CBP processes FOIA requests according to their order of receipt.  Although CBP’s goal is to respond within 20 business days of receipt of your request, FOIA does permit a 10-day extension of this time period in certain circumstances pursuant to 6 C.F.R. Part 5 § 5.5(c). 
 
For additional information please consult CBP FOIA website please click on FOIA Act Resources or visit (http://www.cbp.gov/site-policy-notices/foia) http://www.cbp.gov/site-policy-notices/foia. (http://www.cbp.gov/site-policy-notices/foia) 
Sincerely, 
U.S. Customs and Border Protection

RE: PUBLIC RECORDS REQUEST of July 13, 2025, Reference #C003439-071325 Dear Mr. Clark: Greetings. My name is Joseph Anderson and I am a Deputy Public Records Officer for Skamania County. I assist inreviewing and responding to public records requests (PRRs) for alldepartments. 

On July 13, 2025, we received your public records request for "- Any and all lists, spreadsheets or other organized datasets that detail potential or substantiated allegations of misconduct and/or impeached or impeachable testimony, created under Brady v. Maryland and/or Giglio v. United States. 
- Any and all records regarding substantiated allegations of misconduct or violations of internal department policy or criminal law by specific law enforcement officers. 

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes." 
After reviewing our files, we have located records that are responsive to your request. Please log in to the Skamania County Public Records Center at the following link to retrieve the records responsive to your request: County Public Records Request - C003439-071325 Pleasenote the following information from Skamania County Prosecutor AdamKick with respect to the first part of your request, as writtenabove, regarding Brady or Giglio material: "[Skamania County does not] have a 'Brady list,' per se.There is one deputy that works for the Skamania county Sheriff’s Officefor whom we have potential impeachment information and for whom weprovide a memo summarizing the circumstances. We provide this memo whenrequired to defense counsel on cases involving this deputy. Becausethere is only one local deputy for whom we maintain PID information,there is no list. Just the single memo, which we are happy to provide. [ Potential Impeachment Disclosure memo attached here .] TheWashington State Patrol sometimes sends us information from state-widepotential impeachment issues with WSP employees. We do not maintain thisinformation in any organized way because it does not apply to anyofficers that regularly appear in our courts/cases. I just want toconfirm that these records are not made into any list, and to the extentthat these records are related to WSP employees, are likely bettersought from the WSP directly, if you’re interested in the raw data (inaddition to any lists)." I have been advised by the Sheriff's Office that there are no records responsive to the second portion of your request seeking records regarding substantiated allegations of misconduct or violations of internaldepartment policy or criminal law by specific law enforcement officers. SkamaniaCounty has searched for, attempted to identify, locate, and provide anynon-exempt public records that may be responsive to this request. Since this completely fulfills your request, we are now closing this public records request. The one (1) yearstatute of limitations to seek judicial review under the Public RecordsAct (Chapter 42.56 RCW) begins now because Skamania County does notintend to further address this request. Please note that if you do not review and download your records within thirty (30) days, they may be removed from the system, in which case you will have to start the public records process all over again to receive your requested records. 

Please feel free to contact me if you have any further questions or concerns by replying to this email or at my phone number below. 

Sincerely, 

Joseph Anderson

title: Texas universities: Past and planned student events (University of Texas at San Antonio)

communications.subject: Texas Public Information Act Request: Texas universities: Past and planned student events (University of Texas at San Antonio)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Texas Public Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

This is a survey of events planned or proposed by recognized or registered student organizations (or individual students or faculty members). I am seeking copies of calendar entries for events that were held or proposed. I am not seeking a search of records held by students or student organizations. I am only seeking information held by the university administration (for example, in an Event Management System, which may be helpful in providing a list of past events and proposed future events). 

If this request is unclear or if I could clarify it in any way, please don't hesitate to ask.

I request:

1. All calendar entries (or Event Management System database entries) for events held or sponsored by a registered student organization, individual student, or faculty member during the final two weeks of each term during 2023, 2024, and Winter/Spring 2025. If your institution's academic calendar does not identify a final date of a given term, please use the final day of exams for the term as the final day of the term.

2. All calendar entries (or Event Management System database entries) for events held or sponsored by a registered student organization, individual student, or faculty member after 10:00 p.m. and/or before 8:00 a.m., between January 31, 2023 and July 1, 2025.

3. All calendar entries for events which are or were proposed to be held by a registered student organization, individual student, or faculty member, where the event is proposed to be held after 10:00 p.m. and/or before 8:00 a.m. This request is limited to events that are proposed to be held between July 1, 2025 and July 1, 2026. 

4. All calendar entries for events which are or were proposed to be held by a registered student organization, individual student, or faculty member, where the event is proposed to be during the final two weeks of a term in the Fall 2025, Winter 2025-2026, or Spring 2026 semesters/terms. Please us the same means of calculating "final two weeks" as in (1), above.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Adam Steinbaugh

--- Please respond above this line --- 

This is in response to your Texas Public Information Act (TPIA) request to The University of Texas at San Antonio (UTSA), received in our office on 6/30/2025, wherein you requested, "To Whom It May Concern: 

Pursuant to the Texas Public Information Act, I hereby request the following records: 

This is a survey of events planned or proposed by recognized or registered student organizations (or individual students or faculty members). I am seeking copies of calendar entries for events that were held or proposed. I am not seeking a search of records held by students or student organizations. I am only seeking information held by the university administration (for example, in an Event Management System, which may be helpful in providing a list of past events and proposed future events). 

If this request is unclear or if I could clarify it in any way, please don't hesitate to ask. 

I request: 

1. All calendar entries (or Event Management System database entries) for events held or sponsored by a registered student organization, individual student, or faculty member during the final two weeks of each term during 2023, 2024, and Winter/Spring 2025. If your institution's academic calendar does not identify a final date of a given term, please use the final day of exams for the term as the final day of the term. 

2. All calendar entries (or Event Management System database entries) for events held or sponsored by a registered student organization, individual student, or faculty member after 10:00 p.m. and/or before 8:00 a.m., between January 31, 2023 and July 1, 2025. 

3. All calendar entries for events which are or were proposed to be held by a registered student organization, individual student, or faculty member, where the event is proposed to be held after 10:00 p.m. and/or before 8:00 a.m. This request is limited to events that are proposed to be held between July 1, 2025 and July 1, 2026. 

4. All calendar entries for events which are or were proposed to be held by a registered student organization, individual student, or faculty member, where the event is proposed to be during the final two weeks of a term in the Fall 2025, Winter 2025-2026, or Spring 2026 semesters/terms. Please us the same means of calculating "final two weeks" as in (1), above. 

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes. 

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not. 

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days, as the statute requires. 

Sincerely, 

Adam Steinbaugh 
We have reviewed our files and located the attached documents that are responsive to your request.  Although the TPIA allows a governmental body to charge for copying documents, the attached is provided to you at no charge. 
If you have any questions or wish to discuss this further, you may contact me at 210-458-7500 / 210-458-4105 or via email at publicinfo@utsa.edu. 

Sincerely, Kathleen Blanton Open Records Manager 
The University of Texas at San Antonio 
Office of Legal Affairs - Open Records 
www.utsa.edu/openrecords **If you wish to make or amend an open records request to UTSA you may do so online at www.utsa.edu/openrecords.**

title: ChatGPT EDU user analytics data

communications.subject: California Public Records Act Request: ChatGPT EDU user analytics data
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the California Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

1) A user data export from the university's ChatGPT EDU user analytics dashboard covering the time period January 1, 2025 until the date this request is processed. A description of this data and how to export it from the dashboard are available here: https://help.openai.com/en/articles/10875114-user-analytics-for-chatgpt-enterprise-and-edu. 

Specifically, I am requesting the data export report described in that help article under the heading "User export - column definitions". Several of the data columns in the export ("name" and "email") contain personally identifiable information and I acknowledge that these columns must be redacted or removed from the responsive record.

2) A GPT data export from the university's ChatGPT EDU user analytics dashboard covering the time period January 1, 2025 until the date this request is processed. Specifically, I am requesting the data export report described in the help article linked above under the heading "GPT export - column definitions." I acknowledge that this report contains one data column ("gpt_creator_email") that must be redacted or removed from the responsive record.

I ask that the responsive records be provided as .csv files or in a comparable, data-friendly file type.

I also ask that all fees be waived as the records I have requested are readily available and can be instantly exported from the user analytics dashboard. The necessary redactions can also be done quickly and in mass by removing the relevant columns from the dataset.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 calendar days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Todd Feathers

Dear Todd Feathers, 
I am writing in response to your California Public Records Act request, received on July 02, 2025, seeking: "To Whom It May Concern: 

Pursuant to the California Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records: 

1) A user data export from the university's ChatGPT EDU user analytics dashboard covering the time period January 1, 2025 until the date this request is processed. A description of this data and how to export it from the dashboard are available here: https://help.openai.com/en/articles/10875114-user-analytics-for-chatgpt-enterprise-and-edu. 

Specifically, I am requesting the data export report described in that help article under the heading "User export - column definitions". Several of the data columns in the export ("name" and "email") contain personally identifiable information and I acknowledge that these columns must be redacted or removed from the responsive record. 

2) A GPT data export from the university's ChatGPT EDU user analytics dashboard covering the time period January 1, 2025 until the date this request is processed. Specifically, I am requesting the data export report described in the help article linked above under the heading "GPT export - column definitions." I acknowledge that this report contains one data column ("gpt_creator_email") that must be redacted or removed from the responsive record. 

I ask that the responsive records be provided as .csv files or in a comparable, data-friendly file type. 

I also ask that all fees be waived as the records I have requested are readily available and can be instantly exported from the user analytics dashboard. The necessary redactions can also be done quickly and in mass by removing the relevant columns from the dataset. 

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes. 

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not. 

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 calendar days, as the statute requires. 

Sincerely, 

Todd Feathers

title: Dolores Leschuck Open Records Request

communications.subject: Texas Public Information Act Request: Dolores Leschuck Open Records Request
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Texas Public Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Dear Sir or Madam:

I am submitting this letter in order to request all documents, public information and public records related to Case ID 25000541, described below.  Please be advised that this request is hereby submitted pursuant to The Texas Open Records Act, Texas Government Code Chapter 552, and The Federal Freedom of Information Act.  I would like to request that all such public information and records be produced as soon as possible.  Please be advised that your agency will be paid the requisite fees, in accordance with the Open Records Act, with respect to your compliance with this request for the production of public records and documents.

Our office represents Dolores Leschuck in regard to injuries she sustained in an automobile accident  on April 9, 2025 at approximately 5:48 PM.  The location of the accident was 21100 SE H.K. Dodgen Loop, Temple TX.  The public information and documents which I am requesting at this time (including information that is collected, assembled, or maintained under a law or ordinance or in connection with the transaction of official business by or for a government body, which included the media on which the public information is recorded, paper, film, magnetic, optical, and/or solid state device that can store an electronic signal; tape; computer disk; etc.) are as follows:

•	Any video or photographs taken at the scene of the collision, or in the officer’s cruiser,
 
•	Any bodycam footage captured by responding officers,

•	Any witness statements, handwritten notes, or supplemental accident report information, 

•	An audio copy of the 911 calls from witnesses who called in to report this accident, along with any witness names, addresses, and phone numbers that may be in possession of the communications center, along with any police reports that correspond to this particular incident. 

•	Copies of all sketches, diagrams, witness statements and/or names and phone numbers of witnesses at the scene who did not give statements that may be in the possession of your department.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Vic Feazell
